## Investigating hardware constraints  
- Edge hardware like Jetson imposes limits on power and computational resources, critical for real-time navigation.  
- Research will assess how VLMs/VLAs optimize for these constraints, focusing on deployment in 2024-2025.  
- The analysis will prioritize models balancing accuracy and speed for robotic applications on such platforms.  
- Findings will inform which architectures are viable for low-latency, resource-efficient navigation tasks.  

## Exploring application focus  
- Real-time robotic navigation requires models that process visual and language inputs simultaneously for decision-making.  
- The study will examine how VLMs/VLAs enable robots to interpret environments and follow commands in dynamic settings.  
- Emphasis is on scenarios like obstacle avoidance, path planning, and human-robot interaction on edge devices.  
- Research will highlight models demonstrating robust performance under real-world, time-sensitive conditions.  
- The timeline of 2024-2025 suggests a focus on emerging, practical implementations ready for deployment.  

